{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e9b1d136-fc17-4245-bded-bba2c75565d2","content":"On macOS, the system automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** via ReportCrash whenever a process crashes. No extra setup is needed.\n\n**Look here:**\n- `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` — user-level crashes\n- `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` — system-wide crashes\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp-2026-04-24-014157.ips` and contain the native backtrace, signal info, and loaded images.\n\n**For core dumps** (optional, disabled by default):\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\nsudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/cores/core.%P\n```\n\nThen reproduce the crash — the core file appears at the configured path.\n\n**Tip:** If you need to symbolicate the `.ips` crash log against .NET runtime symbols, the `apple-crash-symbolication` skill can help — just say the word.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"06f3f455-5a47-4b77-ae1c-6c768969cbed","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, specifically without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to search a codebase. Let me provide a concise answer.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates `.ips` crash reports. These are found in:\n\n- `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user apps)\n- `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system-wide)\n\nFor NativeAOT specifically, `createdump` is not included (it's a CoreCLR tool). But macOS generates crash reports automatically via ReportCrash.\n\n\nIf you want actual core dumps instead, those are disabled by default on macOS — you'd need to enable them with `ulimit -c unlimited` and potentially work around System Integrity Protection restrictions.","outputTokens":437,"requestId":"600E:281228:DCAEC1:FFDC53:69EACA65"},"id":"37dfad3c-70f0-4527-b87d-cf6465dce4c1","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:42:08.282Z","parentId":"a2b578b2-e123-4664-8135-e32659b1301f"}
